<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">CARE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold"> (Christian Action Research and Education) (LAI 012)</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.84pt; padding-left:19.61pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">About CARE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> (Christian Action Research and Education</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">)</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">1.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CARE is a well-established mainstream Christian charity providing resources and helping to bring Christian insight and experience to matters of public policy and practical caring initiatives.  This submission is informed by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">our relationship</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">several </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ontline organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that provide care and assistance to those who have experienced exploitation and trafficking </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in addition to our work with MPs and Peers on this subject.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.84pt; padding-left:19.61pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Summary</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">2.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The proposals will have serious consequences for the human rights of vic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tims of human trafficking.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">2.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The proposals will contravene international obligations under the EU Anti-Trafficking Directive 2011/36/EU and will prevent victims of trafficking accessing support they are entitled to under the Directive.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">2.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The proposals will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">disproportionately affect victims of trafficking and will amount to discrimination on the grounds of race or national origin.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.84pt; padding-left:19.61pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Introduction</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This submission is made in relation to the specific effects the proposals in the Transforming Legal Aid paper will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> have on victims of human trafficking.  Although these proposals may have similarly adverse effects on other vulnerable groups or on principles of rule of law in general, CARE’s response is focussed on the impact on one particularly marginalised group with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in our society.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.84pt; padding-left:19.61pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">The proposed introduction of a residence test for civil legal aid claimants, so as to limit legal aid to those with a “strong connection” with the UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">4.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This proposal will obstruct access to legal assistance for victims of human trafficking</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which they are entitled to under EU Directive 2011/36/EU on preventing and combating trafficking in human beings.  Article 12(2) of the Directive states:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">4.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“Member States shall ensure that victims of trafficking in human beings have access without delay to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> legal counselling, and, in accordance with the role of victims in the relevant justice system, to legal representation, including for the purpose of claiming compensation. Legal counselling and legal representation shall be free of charge where the victim</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> does not have sufficient financial resources.”</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">4.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The residence test will completely prevent some victims accessing legal counselling from a trained lawyer and for other victims it will mean a delay of up to 12 months before they can receive this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">assistance.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">4.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The majority of victims of human trafficking identified in the UK come from countries outside the EEA/EU, 64.8 per cent of all victims referred to the National Referral Mechanism in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2012.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Many of these victims will fail the residence test be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cause they will not have been legally resident in the UK prior to being identified as a victim.  Most traffickers will not have gone to the expense of obtaining visas and genuine travel documents for their victims.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Although an individual receives permissio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n to r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eside in the UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> once they are identified as a victim</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, they would need to wait 12 months before becoming eligible for legal aid under the proposed changes.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">4.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The residence test will also affect v</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ictims of trafficking who are nationals of the EEA/EU o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r who have otherwise obtained legal residency in the UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Hope for Justice, a charity which works directly with victims of trafficking has told CARE that 70 per cent of the victims they supported between April 2012 and March 2013 were EU citizens who had re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sided in the UK for less than 12 months.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">4.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The residence test will not only fail the “without delay” aspect of the EU Directive but will in some cases prevent access to justice completely.  Certain types of claim must be brought within strict time limits, w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hich would expire before a victim has achieved the 12 month</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> legal residence.  Victims of exploitative labour practices will be prevented from bringing claims to employment tribunals and victims </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will not be able to apply for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> judicial review of a decision r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">elating to their care (for example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a decision of whether or not they are a victim of trafficking under the National Referral Mechanism).</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">4.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Access to civil legal aid is important for victims of trafficking as it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">provides a way for them to challenge incor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rect decisions made by state authorities through judicial review, but it also enables victims to seek compensation from their traffickers.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Criminal prosecutions of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> those who traffic and exploit others</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> vital, but ensuring victims can pursue their abusers for financial compensation is also key to providing them with justice. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> These potential financial penalties are part of creating strong deterrents </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">against traffickers operating in this country.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; vertical-align:baseline">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">4.8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; vertical-align:baseline">Victims</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; vertical-align:baseline"> of human trafficking do not have the resources to pay for a lawyer without legal aid, but also do not have the capacity to represent themselves in a foreign language, in an unfamiliar legal system.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">4.9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CARE welcomes the proposal to create an exception to the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> residence test for asylum seekers which will apply to some victims of human trafficking.  However, not all victims of trafficking need or wish to apply for asylum.  Some are EEA citizens and others wish to return home to their own country.  This exception</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will not be available to them</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  We believe that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the description of asylum seekers as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">by virtue of their circumstances [...] amongst the most vulnerable in society</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,”</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> could apply equally to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">victims of human trafficking</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  Indeed, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it could be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> argue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">many are more vulnerable since </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the UK has not been a place of safety for them, rather the location of their exploitation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">By not extending an automatic exception to all individuals who are reasonably believed to be victims (having received an affirmative </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“reasonable grounds” decision under the NRM) this proposal unjustly discriminates between victims</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> who apply</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and are eligible</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for asylum and those who do not.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">4.10.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Although the Government claims that the residence test will not contravene obligations under the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">EU Anti-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rafficking Directive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> because it will make sure legal aid will be available via an “exceptional circumstances” process </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“where necessary to comply with obligations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">under EU or national law”</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> we do not believe this will be sufficient. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ithout the adv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ice and assistance of a legal professional, victims of human trafficking will find it extremely difficult to comprehend and make an application for legal aid under this “exceptional circumstances” rule.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he proposed residence test</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> even with the EU law obl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">igations exception</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">effect</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> discriminate against victims on the basis of their native language</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and nationality</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">4.11.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Therefore, CARE is not satisfied by these assurances and recommends instead as a minimum the proposal be amended to exempt victims of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">trafficking from the residence test.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">4.12.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Case Study:  Magdalene</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Magdalene is from Eastern Europe, she came to the UK determined to work her way out of backbreaking poverty. She and her children had fallen into homelessness and she was desperately searching </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">for a better future for her little ones when she was approached by a man offering a better life in the UK. However, when the family arrived things were very different. Magdalene and her family were exploited for fraud and labour.  At the time of rescue Mag</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">dalene and her family had been lawfully resident in the country for less than 12 months. Magdalene is still having problems with housing as a result of her identity documents being taken by the trafficker.  Magdalene is cooperating with a police investigat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ion.  If the new proposals were enacted, Magdalene and her family:</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Would not be able to access legal aid to make an employment tribunal claim within the limitation period;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Would not be able to access legal aid to commence other civil proceedings against th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">e trafficker until she had been in the country 12 months;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Would not be able to access legal aid to deal with her housing issues, rendering the family at risk of being made homeless and subsequently at risk of re-trafficking.  This would then have a direct </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">impact on the criminal case where Magdalene is a key witness.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 0.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-0.55pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.84pt; padding-left:19.61pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">The proposal that providers of legal services in applications for judicial review against public bodies should only be paid for work done on the case if the Court grants permission for the appl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">ication to proceed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Human trafficking cases </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">present many challenges.  Sometimes due to language, psychological trauma or fear</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> victims can be reticent in sharing their stories.  For lawyers providing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">them with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">assistance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> determining the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">facts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and finer legal points of an individual’s case can be a complicated and time-consuming process.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Given that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> mistakes are made by public bodies in the decisions they take in relation to victims of trafficking, the proposal to limit payment for work on judi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cial review applications is likely to result in many victims being unable to bring such cases for judicial review</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and justice not being done</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Law Society and the Young Legal Aid Practitioners Association have both indicated that there will be a reducti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on in the willingness of solicitors to take legal aid cases due to the financial risk created by the proposal.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Individuals who have experienced trafficking and exploitation are unlikely to have the capacity to make these applications themselves due to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">limited English language and a lack of understanding of English law</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  It is unfair that these victims should be denied access to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pursue a complaint against the state by the financial considerations imposed on a legal aid solicitor by the state</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> itself</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.84pt; padding-left:19.61pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">he proposal that legal aid should be removed for all cases assessed as having “borderline” prospects of success.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 40.5pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The current merits test already protects the court and the legal aid budget from expending resources on cases which have little prospect of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">success.  Removing funding from borderline cases could have a detrimental effect on victims of human trafficking.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As has already been mentioned above, the cases of trafficking victims can be complex and the facts can be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">unclear</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> at the start</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  This is ofte</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n a result of the psychological or physical d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">istress a victim is suffering or due to a limited grasp of English.  Under these circumstances initial assessment of the chances of success can be difficult and may mean a case is considered to be “borderline” d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">espite the fact that as further examination takes place the strengths of the case may emerge.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Often these complicated cases which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">draw on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">intricate elements of international and domestic law </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">go </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">form precedent for subsequent cases.  It is clearly in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the public interest for these cases to come to court in order for judges to set guidance for similar future cases.  If legal aid is removed for borderline cases, some of these </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">important cases may be excluded from court which will be detrimental to the deve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lopment of judicial opinion.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As has been previously stated, victims of trafficking who have been through the terrible ordeal of trafficking and exploitation are extremely unlikely to be able to present their own case without legal understanding and in a f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oreign language.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.84pt; padding-left:19.61pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Conclusion</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 40.5pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">7.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> proposed changes will have very serious consequences</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for the protection of the human rights of victims of trafficking specifically the right of access to justice (European Convention on Human Rights Article 6) and the ri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ght not to be discriminated against (ECHR Article 14).  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">7.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Furthermore, the proposals will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">contravene key </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">specific rights to which victims of trafficking are entitled under </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Article 12 of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the EU Directive on combating trafficking in human beings.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">7.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CARE has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">welcomed the announcement by the Home Secretary that the Government plans to introduce a Modern Slavery Bill to improve the UK’s response to slavery and human trafficking.  We feel it would be a backwards step to continue to press ahead with changes to leg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">al aid that would so detrimentally affect those a Modern Slavery Bill would be seeking to protect.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">25 September 2013</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> UK National Referral Mechanism Provisional Statistics 2012. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> The ten most prevalent nationalities/countries of origin in 2012 were Nigeria, Vietnam, Albania, Romania, China, Poland, Slovakia, Lithuania, UK, and Pakistan, five of which are outside the EAA/EU.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/employment-tribunals/taking-a-case-to-an-employment-tribunal"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/employment-tribunals/taking-a-case-to-an-employment-tribunal</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">; Court Procedure Rules 54.5 (1)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Transforming legal aid consultation paper paragraph 3.56 in reference to asylum seekers</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Transformin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">g legal aid consultation paper paragraphs 3.53 and 3.54</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Reproduced with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> kind permission of Hope for Justice</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, this case study was previously submitted to the Ministry of Justice Consultation on  Transforming Legal Aid</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Responses to the Ministry of Justice Transforming Legal Aid Consultation available online here: </span><a href="http://www.younglegalaidlawyers.org/sites/default/files/YLAL%20TLA%20response_final.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.younglegalaidlawyers.org/sites/default/files/YL</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">AL%20TLA%20response_final.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">para</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> 76 and here: </span><a href="http://www.lawsociety.org.uk/representation/policy-discussion/transforming-legal-aid-consultation-law-society-response/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.lawsociety.org.uk/representation/policy-discussion/transfo</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">rming-legal-aid-consultation-law-society-response/</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">para</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> 53</span></p></body></html>